1140","1182":"1182","1115":"1115","1148":"1148","1125":"1125","1146":"1146","1212":"1212","1234":"1234","1145":"1145","1189":"1189","Ham, Somme, Picardie, France":"Ham, Somme, Picardie, Frankrig","Ham, Somme, Picardy, France":"Ham, Somme, Picardie, Frankrig","Ham, Somme, Picardie, França":"Ham, Somme, Picardie, Frankrig","Tripoli, Ţarābulus, Libya":"Tripoli, Ţarābulus, Libyen"},"nl":{"1115–aproximadamente 1182":"1115–circa 1182","1115–1182":"1115–1182","–Male":"Overleden","1125–1182":"1125–1182","1140–1189":"1140–1189","1145–1234":"1145–1234","1148–1212":"1148–1212","1080–1132":"1080–1132","1091–1146":"1091–1146","1091":"1091","1080":"1080","aproximadamente 1182":"circa 1182","1132":"1132","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","1115":"1115","1148":"1148","1125":"1125","1146":"1146","1212":"1212","1234":"1234","1145":"1145","1189":"1189","Ham, Somme, Picardie, France":"Ham, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Ham, Somme, Picardy, France":"Ham, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Ham, Somme, Picardie, França":"Ham, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Tripoli, Ţarābulus, Libya":"Tripoli, Ţarābulus, Libië"},"en":{"1115–aproximadamente 1182":"1115–about 1182","1115–1182":"1115–1182","–Male":"Deceased","1125–1182":"1125–1182","1140–1189":"1140–1189","1145–1234":"1145–1234","1148–1212":"1148–1212","1080–1132":"1080–1132","1091–1146":"1091–1146","1091":"1091","1080":"1080","aproximadamente 1182":"about 1182","1132":"1132","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","1115":"1115","1148":"1148","1125":"1125","1146":"1146","1212":"1212","1234":"1234","1145":"1145","1189":"1189","Ham, Somme, Picardie, France":"Ham, Somme, Picardie, France","Ham, Somme, Picardy, France":"Ham, Somme, Picardie, France","Ham, Somme, Picardie, França":"Ham, Somme, Picardie, France","Tripoli, Ţarābulus, Libya":"Tripoli, Ţarābulus, Libya","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Young, Ok, Nam, Chul, Eun Hee, Eun Young, Hae Jung, Il Hwa.","English (mainly southwestern) and German: variant of   Hamm  .","Dutch: topographic name from <i>ham</i> ‘land in a river bend’, ‘enclosed meadow’, or a habitational name from any of several country houses and places called De(n) Ham. Compare   Van Ham   and   Vanderham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hamme","meanings":["Flemish (<b>Van Hamme</b>): variant of   Ham   2, particularly referring to Hamme, a place in East Flanders.","German and English: variant of   Hamm  ."]},{"name":"Hamm","meanings":["English (London): topographic name for someone who lived at a place called from Middle English <i>ham(me)</i>, <i>hom(me)</i> (Old English <i>hamm</i>), which meant ‘land in a river bend’, ‘land hemmed in by marshland’, ‘wet land hemmed in by higher ground’, ‘river meadow’, or ‘cultivated plot on the edge of woodland or moor’. The topographic term is found mainly in the South Midlands and southern England. There are many farmsteads with this name in Devon and Sussex, five more substantial settlements called Ham or Hamp in Somerset, as well as East and West Ham in Essex, and places called Ham in Gloucestershire, Hampshire, Kent, Surrey, and Wiltshire. This form of the surname is also comparatively frequent in Ireland.","German: topographic name for someone who lived on land in a river bend, Old High German <i>ham</i> (see 1 above).","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from any of numerous places called Hamm, mainly the city in Westphalia."]},{"name":"Hahm","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Sung, Yong, Byung, Chang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jee, Jong, Jong Hun, Jong Hyun, Moon Hee, Jung Suk, Sang, Seok, Seung, Soon, Sungtae, Taeyong.","German: metonymic occupational name for a sealer of weights and measures, from Middle High German <i>hāme</i> ‘(standard) measure’.","Korean: variant of   Ham  ."]},{"name":"Hams","meanings":["English: variant of   Ham   with plural <i>-s</i> or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Lancelin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French: from a pet form of the personal name   Ancel  . Compare   Asselin   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ancel","meanings":["Very common Spanish boy's name (pronounced with a hard g and the stress on the second syllable), a vernacular derivative (via Latin) of Greek <i>angelos</i>, which meant ‘messenger’ in classical Greek, but in New Testament Greek acquired the specialized sense ‘messenger of God’, i.e. an angel. It is common in the U.S. In Britain it is now almost exclusively a girl's name, but it was used occasionally as a boy's name from the 1400s, if not earlier. As such it is familiar as the name of  Angel Clare , the chief male character in  Thomas Hardy's  novel Tess of the D'Urbervilles (  1891 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lancelin de Ham was born in 1115, in Ham, Somme, Picardie, France, his father, Gérard II dit Le Preux DE HAM-DE WALCOURT, was 35 and his mother, Blanche de Breteuil Dame de Breteuil, was 24. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Chlotilde de Roye. He died about 1182, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1115–aproximadamente 1182":"1115–umbes 1182","1115–1182":"1115–1182","–Male":"Surnud","1125–1182":"1125–1182","1140–1189":"1140–1189","11